Scenario 1: Ocean Water Temperature Prediction (Regression)
Problem Statement

The objective of this scenario is to predict ocean water temperature using environmental and depth-related parameters. This is a supervised regression problem where Linear Regression and its optimized variants are applied.

Dataset

Source: Kaggle (Public)

Dataset Name: CalCOFI (California Cooperative Oceanic Fisheries Investigations)

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sohier/calcofi

Target Variable

Water Temperature: T_degC

Input Features

Depth (m)

Salinity

Oxygen

Latitude

Longitude

Tasks Performed

Imported required Python libraries (NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn, Scikit-learn)

Loaded CalCOFI dataset into a Pandas DataFrame

Selected relevant numerical features and target variable

Handled missing values using mean / median imputation

Performed feature scaling using StandardScaler

Split dataset into training and testing sets

Trained a Linear Regression model

Predicted water temperature for test data

Evaluated model performance using:

Mean Squared Error (MSE)

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)

R² Score

Visualized results:

Actual vs Predicted temperature

Residual error plot

Optimized model using:

Feature selection

Regularization techniques (Ridge and Lasso Regression)

Outcome

The optimized regression model was able to predict ocean water temperature with improved accuracy and reduced error, demonstrating the effectiveness of feature scaling and regularization.
Scenario 2: LIC Stock Price Movement Prediction (Classification)
Problem Statement

The goal of this scenario is to classify whether LIC stock price will increase or decrease based on historical stock market data using Logistic Regression.

Dataset

Source: Kaggle (Public)

Dataset Name: LIC Stock Price Data

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/debashis74017/lic-stock-price-data

Target Variable (Derived)

Price Movement

1 → Closing Price > Opening Price

0 → Closing Price ≤ Opening Price

Input Features

Open

High

Low

Volume

Tasks Performed

Imported necessary Python libraries

Loaded LIC stock dataset into Pandas DataFrame

Created a binary target variable (Price Movement)

Handled missing values

Applied feature scaling

Split data into training and testing sets

Trained a Logistic Regression model

Predicted stock price movement

Evaluated classification performance using:

Accuracy

Precision

Recall

F1-Score

Confusion Matrix

Visualized:

ROC Curve

Feature importance

Optimized model using:

Hyperparameter tuning (C, penalty)

Regularization techniques

Outcome

The Logistic Regression model successfully classified stock price movements with good performance metrics, showing the importance of proper feature scaling and regularization.
